"""
MKT Context Commentary — 2 Chronicles chapters 29–31
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-2chronicles-29-31.py

Ch29: Hezekiah's temple purification — 16-day consecration sequence (1st month vv1-17);
     national sin offering with sevenfold animals (vv21-24); Davidic musical order restored
     (vv25-28); Levites outperform priests in preparation (v34)
Ch30: Passover in the second month — Num 9:6-14 legal basis; invitation to northern remnant
     under Assyrian control post-722 BCE; Hezekiah's intercessory prayer for the ritually
     impure (vv18-20); unprecedented 14-day festival (vv23); comparison to Solomon (v26)
Ch31: Tithe reform (Mosaic system restored); Levitical organizational structure (maḥᵉlāqôt);
     temple storage chambers and distribution to priestly cities; Hezekiah summary formula
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(layer, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

CONTEXT = {
  "29": {
    "1": "<p>Hezekiah&rsquo;s accession date is one of the most debated in Old Testament chronology. The standard chronology places his reign at 715&ndash;686 BCE (29 years matching the text), while a co-regency hypothesis suggests 729&ndash;686 BCE. The difficulty arises from synchronizing 2 Kgs 18:1 (Hezekiah&rsquo;s accession in Hoshea&rsquo;s third year) with 2 Kgs 18:9-10 (Samaria&rsquo;s fall in Hezekiah&rsquo;s sixth year = Hoshea&rsquo;s ninth year). The Assyrian annals of Sargon II confirm Samaria&rsquo;s fall in 722&ndash;720 BCE. His mother Abijah daughter of Zechariah is otherwise unknown; the Chronicler records her name as part of the standard Judean accession formula that includes the queen mother (<em>gᵉbîrāh</em>), who had formal court status.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The comparison to David (<em>kaʾăšer ʿāśāh Dāwîd ʾāḇîw</em>) is the Chronicler&rsquo;s highest evaluation for a Judean king; only Hezekiah and Josiah receive this commendation without qualification. In the Deuteronomistic History (2 Kgs 18:5), Hezekiah is credited with a superlative that even David lacks: &lsquo;he trusted in the LORD, the God of Israel, so that there was none like him among all the kings of Judah after him, nor among those before him.&rsquo; The Chronicler expresses the same evaluation through the Davidic comparison formula.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Opening the temple doors in the first month of his first year is Hezekiah&rsquo;s inaugural act — the direct reversal of Ahaz&rsquo;s closure (28:24). The first month (<em>bāḥōdeš hāriʾšôn</em>) = Nisan (March-April in the Babylonian calendar adopted by Israel). The choice of the first month has covenantal significance: it is the month of Passover (Exod 12:2) and the month when the tabernacle was first erected (Exod 40:2, 17). Hezekiah&rsquo;s reform thus begins on the same symbolic calendar position as the wilderness establishment of the cult.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The eastern square (<em>hāreḥôḇ hammizrāḥît</em>) where Hezekiah assembles the priests and Levites is the outer court of the temple on the eastern side — accessible to the Levites and serving as the mustering point for the reform. The separation of priests and Levites as distinct groups reflects the Chronicler&rsquo;s consistent interest in proper cultic role differentiation: only priests can enter the inner sanctuary; Levites handle transport of defilements to the court. This separation governs the division of labor in the purification narrative (vv16ff).</p>",
    "5": "<p>&lsquo;Remove the filth&rsquo; (<em>hôṣîʾû ʾet-hanniddāh</em>) — <em>niddāh</em> (H5079): the term primarily denotes menstrual impurity in Levitical law (Lev 15:19-24; 18:19) and is applied metaphorically to religious defilement throughout the Prophets (Ezra 9:11; Ezek 36:17; Lam 1:17). Its use here for the temple&rsquo;s cultic defilement under Ahaz employs the strongest term of ritual impurity available — menstrual-level uncleanness. The severity of the defilement matches the severity of Ahaz&rsquo;s apostasy (28:24).</p>",
    "6": "<p>The three verbs describing the fathers&rsquo; apostasy — <em>māʿᵃlû</em> (were unfaithful), <em>ʿāzᵃḇû</em> (forsook), <em>wayyasibbû pᵉnêhem</em> (turned their faces away) — constitute a formal indictment using the Chronicler&rsquo;s key vocabulary. <em>māʿal</em> (faithlessness/trespass) is the Chronicler&rsquo;s term for covenant violation; <em>ʿāzaḇ</em> (abandon) is the apostasy verb that triggers the <em>lex talionis</em> of divine abandonment. <em>wayyasibbû ʾet-pᵉnêhem mimmiškan YHWH</em> (&lsquo;they turned their faces away from the LORD&rsquo;s dwelling&rsquo;) inverts the required orientation of prayer and worship toward the temple (1 Kgs 8:38, 44, 48).</p>",
    "7": "<p>Ahaz&rsquo;s specific cultic crimes: shutting the vestibule doors (<em>sāgᵃrû daltôt hāʾûlām</em>), extinguishing the lamps (<em>dikkû ʾet-hannērōt</em>), stopping incense (<em>qᵉṭōret</em>), and halting burnt offerings (<em>ʿōlāh</em>). The lamp (<em>nēr</em>) in the temple menorah was to burn continually before YHWH as a perpetual ritual requirement (Exod 27:20-21; Lev 24:2-4); its extinction was a profound defilement signal. These four cessations correspond to the four primary elements of Israelite sanctuary worship, suggesting a systematic dismantling of Yahwistic cult under Ahaz.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The triad of judgment terms — <em>zᵉʿāwāh</em> (horror), <em>šammāh</em> (devastation/astonishment), <em>šᵉrēqāh</em> (hissing/mockery) — is a fixed prophetic judgment formula appearing in Jeremiah (Jer 18:16; 19:8; 25:9, 18; 29:18) and Deuteronomy (Deut 28:37) as the stereotyped consequences of covenant violation. The formula describes the reaction of horrified observers to a devastated land. Hezekiah&rsquo;s use of prophetic judgment language to describe the current national condition (<em>kaʾăšer ʾattem rōʾîm</em>, &lsquo;as you yourselves can see&rsquo;) invites the priests and Levites to identify the present state of Judah with the prophetically predicted consequences of apostasy.</p>",
    "9": "<p>&lsquo;Our fathers have fallen by the sword, and our sons and daughters and wives are in captivity&rsquo; — Hezekiah references the specific military disasters of Ahaz&rsquo;s reign: the Syro-Ephraimite war (2 Chr 28:5), in which Syria and Israel each took large numbers of Judean captives (28:5, 8, 17-18). The captivity reference establishes a direct causal chain between cultic neglect and military catastrophe — the Chronicler&rsquo;s standard retribution theology: abandoning the cult leads to military defeat and population loss.</p>",
    "10": "<p><em>bᵉrît ʿim-YHWH ʾĕlōhê Yiśrāʾēl</em> (&lsquo;covenant with the LORD&rsquo;) — the Chronicler uses <em>bᵉrît kārat</em> (cut a covenant) for formal covenant renewal ceremonies at critical transitions in national history (cf. 15:12 under Asa; 23:16 under Jehoiada; 34:31 under Josiah). Hezekiah&rsquo;s covenant proposal at the beginning of his reform is the constitutive theological act: the reform is framed as covenant renewal, not merely institutional repair. The purpose: <em>lᵉhāšîḇ ʾet-ḥᵃrôn ʾappô mimmennû</em> (to turn away his fierce anger from us) — the <em>ḥārôn ʾap</em> formula for intense divine wrath.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The direct address to the Levites as <em>bānay</em> (&lsquo;my sons&rsquo;) is unique in Chronicles — Hezekiah speaks to the cult personnel with parental authority. The divine election formula <em>ḇāḵem bāḥar YHWH laʿᵃmōd lᵉpānāyw ûlᵉšārᵉtô</em> (&lsquo;the LORD has chosen you to stand before him and to minister to him&rsquo;) echoes the Deuteronomic formula for the Levitical calling (Deut 10:8; 18:5, 7) and grounds the call to diligence in divine election rather than merely administrative necessity. Election = obligation to non-negligence.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Fourteen Levites are named in three groups corresponding to the three main Levitical clans: Kohathites (Mahath and Joel), Merarites (Kish and Azariah), and Gershonites (Joah and Eden) — the three sons of Levi (Gen 46:11; Num 3:17-20). Two additional groups follow (Elizaphan and the three temple musicians). The careful genealogical specification of the fourteen leaders by both clan and father&rsquo;s name is consistent with the Chronicler&rsquo;s interest in legitimate cultic personnel; all reform activity is performed by the properly qualified Levitical officials.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Shimri and Jeiel from the Elizaphanites — Elizaphan son of Uzziel was a Kohathite clan chief (Num 3:30; 1 Chr 15:8), so this group is a Kohathite subdivision. Zechariah and Mattaniah from Asaph&rsquo;s line — Asaph is David&rsquo;s chief temple musician (1 Chr 6:39; 25:1-2), and his descendants form the primary psalm-singing guild. The inclusion of musical guilds in the purification workforce reflects the Chronicler&rsquo;s understanding that the temple musicians are full cult personnel, not merely entertainers.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Jehiel and Shimei from Heman&rsquo;s sons — Heman is the second of the three Davidic temple music guild heads (1 Chr 6:33; 25:4-6). Shemaiah and Uzziel from Jeduthun&rsquo;s sons — Jeduthun is the third music guild head (1 Chr 25:3; Ps 39, 62, 77 superscription). All three major musical guilds (Asaph, Heman, Jeduthun) participate in the temple purification — consistent with the Chronicler&rsquo;s pattern of integrating musical worship into all major liturgical events.</p>",
    "15": "<p><em>bimṣwat hammelek ʿal-piY YHWH</em> (&lsquo;as the king commanded, by the word of the LORD&rsquo;) — the purification work has dual authority: royal command and divine word. The Chronicler consistently presents legitimate reform as both regally authorized and prophetically grounded. <em>lᵉṭahēr bêt-YHWH</em> (&lsquo;to purify the house of the LORD&rsquo;) — the Piel of <em>ṭāhar</em> is the technical term for ritual cleansing; it involves both physical removal of defiling substances and the declarative act of pronouncing things clean.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The task division between priests and Levites: the priests entered the inner sanctuary (<em>liphᵉnîmāh</em>) — the Holy Place — which only they could enter, while the Levites took the impurities (<em>hanniddāh</em>) from the court to the Kidron Brook. The Kidron Valley (<em>naḥal Qiḏrôn</em>), running between Jerusalem and the Mount of Olives, served as the primary dump for cultic impurities: Asa threw Maacah&rsquo;s Asherah idol there (1 Kgs 15:13); Josiah disposed of Baal and Asherah materials there (2 Kgs 23:4-6, 12). The stream carried the defilements away from the sacred precincts.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The 16-day consecration chronology: they began on the first day of the first month, reached the vestibule (<em>ûlᵉʾûlām YHWH</em>) by the eighth day, and completed the entire temple complex by the sixteenth day. The eight-day phase structure mirrors the dedication sequence of 2 Chr 7:8-10 (seven days for dedication plus one) and anticipates the eight-day structure of ch30&rsquo;s Passover (7 days + 7 days more). Completing the purification by the sixteenth of Nisan left enough time for the regular Passover (fourteenth of Nisan) to be celebrated — but in fact the second-month Passover is chosen (30:2-3) because insufficient preparation time and personnel were available.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The priests&rsquo; report to Hezekiah specifies two objects separately: <em>mizbēaḥ hāʿōlāh</em> (the altar of burnt offering) with all its vessels and <em>šulḥan hammaʿăreket</em> (the table of the showbread) with all its vessels. The showbread table (<em>leḥem happānîm</em>, bread of the presence) held twelve loaves representing the twelve tribes in perpetual divine presence (Exod 25:23-30; Lev 24:5-9). Its specific mention alongside the altar indicates that both the sacrificial system and the symbolic covenant meal before YHWH have been restored.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The vessels Ahaz set aside (<em>hisîḡ ʾAḥāz</em>) during his reign — the Piel of <em>sûg</em> means to push aside, remove from proper use. Ahaz&rsquo;s appropriation of temple vessels for other purposes (28:24 mentions closing the temple, cutting up the temple vessels) is reversed: the same vessels are prepared and consecrated. The phrase <em>bᵉmaʿᵃlô</em> (&lsquo;during his unfaithful reign&rsquo;) uses the noun <em>maʿal</em> (faithlessness/trespass) to characterize Ahaz&rsquo;s entire reign as a single act of covenant violation.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Hezekiah&rsquo;s immediate response to the purification report — rising early (<em>wayyaškem</em>: to arise early, start at dawn) — reflects the urgency and devotion that characterizes the properly faithful king in Chronicles. <em>wayyaʿal bêt YHWH</em> (&lsquo;went up to the LORD&rsquo;s house&rsquo;): the king himself leads the rededication ceremony rather than delegating it to the priests. The assembly of the city&rsquo;s officials (<em>śārê hāʿîr</em>) makes the rededication a civic as well as cultic event.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Seven of each animal — <em>šiḇᵃʿāh pārîm ûšiḇᵃʿāh ʾêlîm ûšiḇᵃʿāh kᵉḇāśîm ûšiḇᵃʿāh śᵉʿîrê ʿizzîm</em> — is a non-standard offering number. The standard sin offering for a ruler is one male goat (Lev 4:22-26); for the congregation, a male goat plus a burnt offering (Lev 4:27-35). The seven of each type suggests a completeness offering (seven = the number of completion in Hebrew) proportionate to the scope of the purification: this is not an individual sin offering but a national purification that requires comprehensive ritual expression. The offering covers three areas: <em>hammamlāḵāh</em> (the kingdom), <em>hammiqdāš</em> (the sanctuary), and <em>Yᵉhûdāh</em> (Judah).</p>",
    "22": "<p>The blood-sprinkling sequence — bulls, rams, lambs — follows the prescribed Aaronic procedure of Lev 1 and 4: slaughter by the offerer (or in this case, the Levitical assistants), blood received by the priests, and sprinkled on the sides of the altar. The priestly role in blood manipulation is carefully maintained even as the scale of the offering required Levitical assistance in slaughter. The three-fold repetition (&lsquo;they slaughtered... and the priests received the blood and sprinkled it on the altar&rsquo;) emphasizes the procedural regularity across all animal types.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The laying of hands (<em>wayyismᵉḵû ʾet-yᵉdêhem</em>) on the sin-offering goats — the <em>sᵉmîḵāh</em> (laying-on of hands) is the prescribed act of identification between the offerer and the sacrifice (Lev 4:4, 15, 24, 29). The offerer presses both hands on the animal&rsquo;s head, signaling that the animal&rsquo;s death is substitutionary for the offerer. Here the king and the whole assembly perform the act collectively — the corporate identification of the national community with the atoning sacrifice. This is the cultic drama of substitutionary atonement enacted for the entire covenant people.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The Hiphil <em>ḥiṭṭᵉʾû</em> (&lsquo;made a sin offering&rsquo;) uses the denominative from <em>ḥaṭṭāʾt</em> (sin offering) — the priests perform the sin-offering rites. The scope is explicit: <em>lᵉḵol-Yiśrāʾēl</em> (for all Israel) — this is not merely a Judean ceremony but a national purification with pan-Israelite scope. The Chronicler&rsquo;s pan-Israelite vision for Hezekiah&rsquo;s reform is established from the outset: the king acts as representative of the undivided twelve-tribe people even when only Judah is physically present. The Passover invitation in ch30 will make this geographic and tribal scope explicit.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The musical instruments — <em>mᵉṣiltayim ûbinᵉḇālîm ûḇᵉḵinnōrôt</em> (cymbals, harps, and lyres) — correspond exactly to the instruments prescribed by David for the temple liturgy (1 Chr 15:16, 19-21; 25:1-8). The threefold authority cited for the musical order: <em>bᵉyad Dāwîd</em> (by the hand of David), <em>Gāḏ ḥōzeh hammelek</em> (Gad the king&rsquo;s seer), and <em>Nātān hannāḇîʾ</em> (Nathan the prophet). This triple prophetic-royal authorization for the Davidic musical system elevates it to the level of Mosaic law: the Davidic musical arrangement was itself a prophetically commanded institution, not merely a royal preference.</p>",
    "26": "<p>The Levites stood with the instruments of David (<em>biklê Dāwîd</em>) — the specific instruments David prescribed — while the priests held the trumpets (<em>baḥăṣōṣrôt</em>). The trumpet was the specifically priestly instrument (Num 10:1-10), used to signal sacred assemblies and sacrificial moments. The division of musical roles between trumpets (priests) and stringed/percussion instruments (Levites) reflects the precise organizational structure of 1 Chr 25 and maintains proper cultic role differentiation even within the unified liturgical act.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The synchronized beginning of burnt offering and song is the narrative&rsquo;s musical climax: <em>ûbᵉhēḥel hāʿōlāh hēḥēl šîr-YHWH wᵉhahăṣōṣrôt</em> (&lsquo;at the moment the burnt offering began, the song to the LORD also began, with the trumpets&rsquo;). This synchronization — sacrifice and song beginning simultaneously — reflects the Chronicler&rsquo;s theology that music is not background entertainment but an integral component of the sacrificial act itself. The instruments of David (<em>ûkᵉlê Dāwîd melek-Yiśrāʾēl</em>) are cited again, anchoring the contemporary liturgy to the Davidic institution.</p>",
    "28": "<p>&lsquo;The whole congregation bowed in worship while the singers sang and the trumpeters sounded, continuing until the burnt offering was complete&rsquo; — the duration of the prostration (<em>kol-haqqāhāl mištaḥᵃwîm</em>) equals the duration of the offering and musical performance. The corporate prostration of the entire assembly while the sacrifice burns is the Chronicler&rsquo;s model of properly integrated worship: cultic action (sacrifice), musical praise, and congregational posture all synchronized. This integration of music, sacrifice, and prostration became the template for Second Temple liturgical practice.</p>",
    "29": "<p>At the completion of the burnt offering (<em>ûkᵉḵallôt hāʿōlāh</em>), the king and all present (<em>hammeleḵ wᵉkol-hannimsāʾîm ʾittô</em>) bowed and worshipped — the conclusion of the rededication ceremony with a corporate act of prostration. The participants described as <em>hannimsāʾîm ʾittô</em> (those found with him) echoes the Chronicler&rsquo;s frequent use of this phrase for the group accompanying the king in religious acts, emphasizing shared participation in the act rather than vicarious observance.</p>",
    "30": "<p>Hezekiah commands the Levites to sing praise in the words of David and Asaph the seer (<em>bᵉdiḇrê Dāwîd ûʾĀsāp hāḥōzeh</em>) — the Psalter is explicitly cited as the content of temple liturgical song. Asaph is designated a <em>ḥōzeh</em> (seer/visionary) rather than merely a musician, reflecting the prophetic authority attributed to the Davidic psalmists in Chronicles (cf. 1 Chr 25:1-3, where the musicians &lsquo;prophesy&rsquo;). The temple musicians are not performers but prophetic voices; their psalms are prophetically inspired compositions, not merely artistic productions.</p>",
    "31": "<p>Hezekiah&rsquo;s invitation — <em>ʿatāh millēʾtem yedḵem lYHWH</em> (&lsquo;now that you have consecrated yourselves to the LORD&rsquo;) — echoes the Mosaic formula for completed consecration (cf. Exod 32:29; 1 Chr 29:5). The invitation to bring <em>zᵉḇāḥîm wᵉtôḏôt</em> (sacrifices and thank offerings) is the invitation to the responsive phase of worship: the national sin offering has been completed; now the people respond with voluntary thanksgiving. <em>kol-nᵉḏîḇ lēḇ</em> (all who were willing of heart) — the freewill-offering language echoes the tabernacle construction (Exod 35:5, 22, 29), where the same idiom describes the generous voluntary response of the community.</p>",
    "32": "<p>The burnt offerings from the congregation: 70 bulls, 100 rams, 200 lambs — <em>kol-ʾēlleh lᵉʿōlāh lYHWH</em> (all for a burnt offering to the LORD). The scale vastly exceeds the royal rededication offering of seven animals per type (v21). The numbers — 70, 100, 200 — are round multiples suggesting schematic totaling rather than precise census figures; the Chronicler uses them to convey the magnitude of popular participation. The distinction between the official rededication offering (vv21-24) and the popular voluntary response (vv31-33) marks a structural shift from institutional to popular worship.</p>",
    "33": "<p>Consecrated offerings (<em>haqqᵉdāšîm</em>): 600 oxen and 3,000 sheep — the <em>qeḏāšîm</em> here are dedicated/vowed animals, a category broader than the required offerings and including animals voluntarily dedicated to divine service. The scale — 3,600 total animals — matches the scale of Solomon&rsquo;s dedication (cf. 2 Chr 7:5: 22,000 oxen and 120,000 sheep, which is ten times larger). The proportional comparison suggests Hezekiah&rsquo;s dedication, while not matching the founding scale, is the most significant national offering since the temple&rsquo;s original dedication.</p>",
    "34": "<p>&lsquo;There were not enough priests to skin all the burnt offerings, so their Levite brothers helped them&rsquo; — the skinning of burnt offerings was technically a priestly function (Lev 1:6); the Levites&rsquo; assistance reflects emergency provision for an extraordinary situation. The explanation: <em>kî halᵉwiyyim yāšᵃrû lᵉbābām lᵉhiqqaddēš mêhakkōhᵃnîm</em> (&lsquo;for the Levites had been more diligent in consecrating themselves than the priests&rsquo;) is an implicit critique of priestly slowness in preparation that recurs in the Hezekiah narrative. The Levites&rsquo; superior readiness is a Chronicler theme: those who responded immediately to the reform call were more prepared than the established priestly institution.</p>",
    "35": "<p>The comprehensive scope of restored worship: burnt offerings (<em>ʿōlāh</em>), fat (<em>ḥeḵel</em>) of fellowship offerings (<em>šᵉlāmîm</em>), and drink offerings (<em>nᵉsāḵîm</em>) for each burnt offering. The drink offering (<em>nesek</em>) is the wine poured out alongside each burnt offering (Num 15:1-12; 28:7) — its restoration signals the complete re-establishment of the prescribed sacrificial system rather than a partial restoration. <em>wayyikkôn ʿăḇōdat bêt-YHWH</em> (&lsquo;the service of the LORD&rsquo;s house was restored to order&rsquo;) — <em>kûn</em> in the Niphal: established, set in order; the same verb used for the establishment of David&rsquo;s kingdom (1 Chr 17:14).</p>",
    "36": "<p><em>wayyiśmaḥ Yᵉḥizqiyyāhû wᵉkol-hāʿām ʿal ʾăšer hēkîn hāʾĕlōhîm lāʿām kî bᵉphitᵉʾôm hāyāh haddāḇār</em> (&lsquo;Hezekiah and all the people rejoiced over what God had prepared for the people, for it had all happened so quickly&rsquo;) — <em>pithʾōm</em> (H6597): suddenly, unexpectedly. The speed of the purification — completed in sixteen days from a standing start — is attributed directly to divine preparation (<em>hēkîn hāʾĕlōhîm</em>): God himself had prepared the circumstances for the rapid reform. The theological point is that the reform&rsquo;s success was not due to human organizational efficiency but divine enabling.</p>"
  },
  "30": {
    "1": "<p>The invitation letters to &lsquo;all Israel and Judah&rsquo; and specifically to &lsquo;Ephraim and Manasseh&rsquo; — written after the 722&ndash;720 BCE Assyrian conquest of the Northern Kingdom (2 Kgs 17) — address an audience that no longer exists as an independent political entity. The northern tribes are under Assyrian provincial administration; the invitation is addressed to the surviving remnant population that was not deported. Hezekiah&rsquo;s reach into Assyrian-controlled territory for a religious invitation reflects the Chronicler&rsquo;s pan-Israelite vision: political division does not dissolve covenantal unity. The mention of Ephraim and Manasseh by name (the two largest and most central northern tribes) is strategic outreach.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The legal basis for a second-month Passover: Num 9:6-14 explicitly provides for individuals unable to celebrate the Passover in the first month (due to corpse defilement or being on a distant journey) to celebrate it exactly one month later — the fourteenth of the second month. Hezekiah&rsquo;s innovation is to apply this individual provision at a national level. The legal reasoning requires consensus: <em>wayyiwwāʿaṣ hammelek wᵉśārāyw wᵉkol-haqqāhāl</em> (the king consulted with his officials and the whole congregation) — this is a royal-assembly decision, not a unilateral royal action.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The two reasons given for the second-month choice: (1) insufficient consecrated priests (<em>lōʾ-yāḵᵉlû lāʿăśōtāh bāʿēt hahîʾ kî hakᵉhānîm lōʾ-hiqqaddᵉšû lᵉdî</em>) and (2) the people had not assembled in Jerusalem (<em>wᵉhāʿām lōʾ-ʾāsᵃpû</em>). The priestly consecration backlog is confirmed by v34 of ch29. The assembly problem reflects the logistics of gathering a dispersed population including northerners — impossible to achieve before the fourteenth of the first month given the short preparation window after the temple purification (completed on the sixteenth of the first month, v17).</p>",
    "4": "<p>&lsquo;The plan seemed right to the king and the whole assembly&rsquo; (<em>wayyiṭᵉšar haddāḇār bᵉʿênê hammelek ûḇᵉʿênê kol-haqqāhāl</em>) — the consensus-approval formula marks the second-month Passover as the result of genuine corporate deliberation. The Chronicler&rsquo;s emphasis on assembly (<em>qāhāl</em>) decision-making throughout Hezekiah&rsquo;s reform demonstrates a model of legitimate royal-communal governance: even the king&rsquo;s religious initiatives require assembly ratification.</p>",
    "5": "<p>&lsquo;From Beersheba to Dan&rsquo; (<em>miBᵉʾēr-šāḇaʿ wᵉʿad-Dān</em>) — the standard phrase for the geographic extent of all Israel (cf. Judg 20:1; 2 Sam 3:10), here applied to the Passover summons. Beersheba was at the southern limit of Judah; Dan at the northern limit of the former Northern Kingdom, now under Assyrian control. The geographic formula asserts the Israelite unity claim that underlies the entire Passover initiative. The note that the Passover <em>lōʾ-ʿāśūhû lāhōḇ</em> had not been kept as prescribed (in great numbers) acknowledges the historical irregularity of national Passover observance.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The royal couriers (<em>hārāṣîm</em>: runners, express messengers) carried official letters (<em>ʾiggᵉrôt</em>) throughout Israel and Judah. The call to &lsquo;return to the LORD, the God of Abraham, Isaac, and Israel&rsquo; — using the patriarchal names (<em>ʾĂḇrāhām Yiṣḥāq wᵉYiśrāʾēl</em>) rather than the usual &lsquo;God of your fathers&rsquo; — deliberately invokes the covenant ancestors as the foundation for the return invitation. The promise to the northern remnant (<em>šᵉʾērît hannimleṭet lākem</em>, survivors who have escaped): even the Assyrian captives might benefit if those who remain return to YHWH.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The negative example of &lsquo;your fathers and brothers who were unfaithful&rsquo; (<em>mᵉʿᵃlû ḇaYHWH</em>) explicitly references the fate of the Northern Kingdom. <em>wayyittᵉnēm lᵉšammāh</em> (&lsquo;he made them a horror&rsquo;) — the same judgment-term (<em>šammāh</em>) used in 29:8 for Judah&rsquo;s own condition. The Chronicler uses the Northern Kingdom&rsquo;s fate as a cautionary lesson for both the northern remnant and the southern kingdom: the pattern of unfaithfulness → desolation is well-established and repeatable.</p>",
    "8": "<p>&lsquo;Do not be stiff-necked like your ancestors&rsquo; (<em>ʾal-taqšû ʿarᵉpᵉḵem</em>) — <em>qāšāh ʿōrep</em> (stiff neck/hard neck) is the standard Pentateuchal description of Israelite stubbornness before YHWH (Exod 32:9; 33:3, 5; 34:9; Deut 9:6, 13). The letter cites the Mosaic tradition explicitly as the ground for its appeal. <em>lāḇôʾ lᵉmiqdāšô ʾăšer hiqdîš lᵉʿôlām</em> (&lsquo;come to his sanctuary, which he has consecrated forever&rsquo;) — the temple&rsquo;s eternal consecration is the basis for its continued validity as a worship center even after the Assyrian crisis.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The promise of compassion from captors (<em>yᵉraḥᵃmûkem ᵃšîḇêhem</em>) for those in Assyrian exile is the only explicit hope expressed in the letter for the deported northerners. The logic: if the northern remnant returns to YHWH, their deported relatives (<em>ʾaḥêḵem ûḇᵉnêḵem</em>) will find compassion from their Assyrian captors and return. This reflects ANE diplomatic practice where a conquered people&rsquo;s religious reform could affect their political status with the conqueror. The theological ground: <em>ḥannûn wᵉraḥûm YHWH ʾĕlōhêḵem</em> (the LORD your God is gracious and merciful) — the Mosaic creed of divine character (Exod 34:6) becomes the pastoral basis for the appeal.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The mockery by the northerners — <em>wayyihyû mᵉśaḥᵃqîm ʿălêhem ûmalbizîm</em> (they laughed and mocked at them) — reflects the social-political reality of the northern population under Assyrian governance. The remnant communities that remained after the 722 BCE deportation had adapted to the new political and religious reality, including the syncretic worship described in 2 Kgs 17:24-41 (the settlers from Babylon, Cuthah, and other regions brought by Assyria, mixing their own cults with vestigial YHWH-worship). Hezekiah&rsquo;s purely Yahwistic invitation would have seemed politically dangerous and religiously archaic to them.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The positive response from some in three northern tribes: Asher, Manasseh, and Zebulun. These three tribes are geographically distributed across the former Northern Kingdom&rsquo;s territory (Asher = far northwest/Galilee coast; Manasseh = central highlands; Zebulun = lower Galilee). Their response is characterized as <em>kāniʿû</em> (they humbled themselves) — the same verb used for proper response to prophetic rebuke (cf. 12:6-7; 30:6, 8; 32:26; 33:12). Humbling oneself before YHWH is the prerequisite for all genuine cultic participation in Chronicles.</p>",
    "12": "<p>&lsquo;God&rsquo;s hand gave them one heart&rsquo; (<em>ûḇîhûdāh hāyᵉtāh yad hāʾĕlōhîm lātēt lāhem lēḇ ʾeḥāḏ</em>) — the divine unification of Judah&rsquo;s heart to carry out the reform is the Chronicler&rsquo;s standard explanation for human unanimity in religious matters. <em>lēḇ ʾeḥāḏ</em> (one heart) echoes the promise of Jer 32:39 (&lsquo;I will give them one heart and one way&rsquo;) and Ezek 11:19 (&lsquo;I will give them an undivided heart&rsquo;). The unanimity is not achieved by political pressure but by divine action.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The &lsquo;Festival of Unleavened Bread&rsquo; (<em>ḥag hammaṣṣôt</em>) in the second month — the seven-day festival following Passover (Lev 23:6-8; Num 28:17-25) is celebrated here as the context for the great assembly. The two festivals (Passover = 14th of the month; Unleavened Bread = 15th-21st) are distinct in Mosaic law but closely connected in practice. The assembly (<em>qāhāl rab mᵉʾōd</em>, a very great assembly) represents the largest gathering since Solomon&rsquo;s dedication — the comparison in v26 will make this explicit.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The spontaneous iconoclasm — removing altars (<em>hammizᵉḇᵉḥôt</em>) and incense altars (<em>hammiqṭārôt</em>) from Jerusalem and throwing them into the Kidron Brook — precedes the formal Passover celebration. The worshippers&rsquo; own initiative in purifying the city before the feast reflects the Passover requirement of removing leaven (Exod 12:15) extended to all forms of ritual impurity. The Kidron as the dump for cultic impurities (cf. 29:16) is used again; the brook functions as the ritual boundary between the sacred city and the profane world beyond.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The slaughter of the Passover lamb on the fourteenth day of the second month precisely fulfills the Num 9:6-14 provision — the lamb killed on the fourteenth, the festival lasting the fifteenth through twenty-first. The priests and Levites&rsquo; shame (<em>wayyēḇōšû</em>) at their insufficient consecration level — compared to the laity&rsquo;s enthusiasm — is the same theme as 29:34: the institutional personnel lag behind the popular religious momentum. Their response: consecrating themselves and bringing burnt offerings into the LORD&rsquo;s house as an act of self-correction.</p>",
    "16": "<p>&lsquo;They took their positions as prescribed, following the law of Moses the man of God&rsquo; (<em>wayyaʿᵃmᵉdû ʿal-ʿomᵉdām kᵉmišpāṭām kᵉtôrat Mōšeh ʾîš-hāʾĕlōhîm</em>) — the Mosaic prescriptions govern both position and procedure; each cult official stands at their assigned station. The Levites received blood (<em>haldūyîm lᵉqabbēl</em>) and the priests sprinkled it — a procedural adaptation from the normal Passover practice (Exod 12:21-27, where each family slaughters its own lamb) to a centralized temple liturgy. The Chronicler is aware that the original Passover was a household observance; the centralized temple version is an adaptation for national assembly.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The Levites slaughtering the Passover lambs for the ritually unclean is a significant extension of the Passover provisions. Normally each family slaughtered its own animal (Exod 12:3-6); here the Levites act as sacrificial proxies for the ritually impure. This reflects a pastoral-theological decision: better to allow the unclean to participate through Levitical mediation than to exclude them from the national covenant feast. The Levites&rsquo; role expands here beyond what the Mosaic texts specify, demonstrating the flexibility of the Chronicler&rsquo;s approach to ritual within the framework of seeking YHWH with a right heart.</p>",
    "18": "<p>&lsquo;A large number of people from Ephraim, Manasseh, Issachar, and Zebulun had not purified themselves, yet they ate the Passover contrary to what was written&rsquo; — four northern tribes are explicitly named as ritually non-compliant participants. The Chronicler does not condemn them for this but records Hezekiah&rsquo;s intercession. The phrase <em>kî ʾāḵᵉlû min-happesaḥ bᵉlōʾ kakkātûḇ</em> (&lsquo;they ate the Passover contrary to what was written&rsquo;) is a frank acknowledgment of ritual non-compliance; the Chronicler&rsquo;s pastoral resolution (vv18b-20) is that sincere heart + seeking God = valid worship despite ritual irregularity.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Hezekiah&rsquo;s intercessory prayer for the ritually impure: <em>kol-lēḇāḇô hēḵîn liḏrōš ʾet-hāʾĕlōhîm YHWH</em> (&lsquo;everyone who has set his heart to seek God, the LORD, the God of his ancestors&rsquo;) — the criterion for valid participation is heart-intention (<em>hēḵîn lēḇ</em> = prepared/set the heart), not ritual compliance. The phrase <em>wᵉlōʾ kᵉṭohrat haqqōḏeš</em> (&lsquo;even if not cleansed according to the sanctuary&rsquo;s rules&rsquo;) explicitly names the ritual deficit while subordinating it to the motivational criterion. This is one of the Hebrew Bible&rsquo;s clearest pastoral statements that sincere seeking of YHWH can compensate for involuntary ritual non-compliance.</p>",
    "20": "<p><em>wayyišmaʿ YHWH ʾel-Yᵉḥizqiyyāhû wayyirpāʾ ʾet-hāʿām</em> (&lsquo;the LORD listened to Hezekiah and healed the people&rsquo;) — the healing (<em>rāpāʾ</em>) in response to intercessory prayer is the direct answer to the ritual irregularity. The verb <em>rāpāʾ</em> can mean both physical healing and the removal of guilt/impurity; here it most naturally means the ritual/moral healing of the impurity that would have made their Passover participation invalid. YHWH&rsquo;s acceptance of the impure participants through Hezekiah&rsquo;s intercession is the structural parallel to the High Priest&rsquo;s annual atonement covering Israel&rsquo;s inadvertent sins (Lev 16:16).</p>",
    "21": "<p>Seven days of celebration with great joy (<em>bᵉśimḥāh gᵉdôlāh</em>) — the Levites and priests praised the LORD daily with <em>kᵉlê-ʿōz lYHWH</em> (resounding instruments for YHWH; <em>ʿōz</em> = strength/loud; instruments of power). The term <em>kᵉlê-ʿōz</em> appears only here and Ps 150:4; the expression captures the volume and intensity of the temple musical performance. The daily praise throughout the seven-day feast represents a sustained liturgical performance unprecedented in Hezekiah&rsquo;s reign and perhaps since Solomon&rsquo;s dedication.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Hezekiah spoke <em>ʿal-lēḇ kol-halᵉwiyyim haMaskîlîm śēḵel ṭôḇ laYHWH</em> (&lsquo;encouragingly to all the Levites who showed skill and understanding in the LORD&rsquo;s service&rsquo;) — <em>maśkîl śēḵel ṭôḇ</em>: Levites with good skill/insight in YHWH&rsquo;s service. The <em>maśkîl</em> (one who has skill or insight) appears as a psalm superscription title (Pss 32, 42, 44, 45 et al.) connected to skilled musical-didactic composition. Fellowship offerings (<em>šᵉlāmîm</em>) throughout seven days plus confession of praise (<em>mîtᵉwaddîm</em>; from <em>yādāh</em> in Hithpael = giving thanks/confessing) combine sacrificial and verbal worship.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The unanimous decision to extend the festival another seven days (<em>lāʿăśôt yāmîm šiḇᵃʿāh ʾăḥērîm</em>) — a spontaneous popular extension of the festival beyond the prescribed seven days. This extension has no Mosaic precedent; it is an act of pure devotional enthusiasm. Only Solomon&rsquo;s dedication (2 Chr 7:8-10) provides a partial parallel: Solomon&rsquo;s feast ran eight days (seven for the Feast of Booths + one day of assembly). Hezekiah&rsquo;s fourteen total days (7+7) thus exceeds any previous festival duration, marking his Passover as uniquely joyful in Israel&rsquo;s history.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The quantitative scale of royal and official contributions: Hezekiah gave 1,000 bulls and 7,000 sheep for the congregation; the officials gave 1,000 bulls and 10,000 sheep. The total — 2,000 bulls and 17,000 sheep — is enormous but less than Solomon&rsquo;s dedication (22,000 oxen + 120,000 sheep; 2 Chr 7:5). The priestly consecrations during the extended festival (<em>wᵉkōhᵃnîm harbēh hiqqaddāšû</em>) echoes 29:34: the priestly preparation that was insufficient for the initial reform catches up during the extended feast.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The full enumeration of who rejoiced: the whole congregation of Judah (<em>kol-qᵉhal Yᵉhûdāh</em>), the priests, the Levites, all who came from Israel (<em>haqqāhāl habbāʾ mêYiśrāʾēl</em>), the foreigners who came from Israel (<em>wᵉhagārîm haggārîm meʾereṣ Yiśrāʾēl</em>), and those living in Judah. The <em>gārîm</em> (resident aliens) participating in the Passover is explicitly grounded in the Mosaic law (Exod 12:48-49; Num 9:14), which permits circumcised resident aliens to celebrate. The pan-Israelite and even multi-ethnic scope of the celebration is the Chronicler&rsquo;s fullest expression of inclusive covenant community.</p>",
    "26": "<p>&lsquo;There was great joy in Jerusalem — nothing like it since the time of Solomon son of David king of Israel&rsquo; — the explicit comparison to Solomon&rsquo;s dedication festivals positions Hezekiah&rsquo;s Passover as the single most significant liturgical event in the entire post-Solomonic period. The Chronicler&rsquo;s comparison is also a theological claim: Hezekiah&rsquo;s reform has restored Judah to the quality of covenant life that prevailed under the united monarchy. This comparison recurs in the Josiah narrative (35:18: &lsquo;no Passover like it had been kept in Israel since the days of Samuel the prophet&rsquo;) — both reformers restore what was lost.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The priests and Levites&rsquo; blessing (<em>yᵉḇārᵉḵû ʾet-hāʿām</em>) is the formal Aaronic blessing of Num 6:22-27, the prescribed priestly act for dismissing the congregation after worship. <em>wayyiqqaḇēl qôlām</em> (&lsquo;their voice was heard&rsquo;) — the passive is significant: the priests&rsquo; voice was received/accepted by God, not merely heard by the congregation. <em>wayyāḇōʾ tᵉpillātām lᵉmᵉʿôn qoḏšô laššāmāyim</em> (&lsquo;their prayer ascended to his holy dwelling place — to heaven&rsquo;) — the ascending prayer formula at the Passover&rsquo;s conclusion (cf. Solomon&rsquo;s prayer reaching heaven in 2 Chr 6:21, 23, 25). The feast ends with the confirmation that the prayers have reached the divine throne.</p>"
  },
  "31": {
    "1": "<p>The spontaneous iconoclastic campaign following the Passover — extending into Ephraim and Manasseh — reflects the spiritual energy of the assembly dispersing homeward. The reform action covers the full range of pagan installations: <em>maṣṣēḇôt</em> (sacred pillars/standing stones, often associated with Canaanite Baal worship), <em>ʾăšērîm</em> (Asherah poles/trees), <em>bāmôt</em> (high places), and <em>mizbᵉḥôt</em> (altars). The geographic scope — Judah, Benjamin, Ephraim, and Manasseh — mirrors the Passover invitation&rsquo;s scope (30:1). The northern iconoclasm is remarkable: Ephraim and Manasseh are under Assyrian provincial administration, yet Judean worshippers apparently conducted religious demolition there without Assyrian intervention — either Hezekiah had diplomatic cover or the Assyrians tolerated this as a minor religious matter.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The Levitical organizational structure (<em>maḥᵉlāqôt</em>) restored by Hezekiah corresponds to the elaborate system established by David in 1 Chr 23-26. The fourfold service description: <em>lᵉʿōlôt ûlišlāmîm ûlᵉšārēt ûlᵉhôdôt ûlᵉhallēl</em> (for burnt offerings, peace offerings, ministering, giving thanks, and praising) integrates sacrificial, administrative, and musical functions into a unified structure. <em>bᵉšaʿarê maḥᵃnôt YHWH</em> (&lsquo;at the gates of the LORD&rsquo;s encampment&rsquo;) — the unusual term <em>maḥăneh</em> (encampment/camp) for the temple complex evokes the wilderness tabernacle as a traveling sanctuary; the temple is the permanent fulfillment of what the camp portable shrine anticipated.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The king&rsquo;s contribution from his personal resources (<em>mêrᵉkûšô</em>) for the required daily offerings is the Chronicler&rsquo;s evidence of Hezekiah&rsquo;s personal sacrificial commitment. The listed offerings correspond to the Mosaic prescription of Num 28-29: <em>hāʿōlôt labbōqer wᵉlāʿereḇ</em> (morning and evening burnt offerings = the <em>tāmîd</em>, Num 28:1-8), Sabbath offerings (Num 28:9-10), new moon offerings (Num 28:11-15), and appointed feast offerings (Num 28:16-29:40). The king personally funding the required public offerings — not merely the voluntary ones — is an act of royal patronage that ensures the full Mosaic sacrificial calendar is maintained regardless of popular contributions.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The command for Jerusalem residents to give the priests&rsquo; and Levites&rsquo; portion (<em>lātēt mānat hakᵉhānîm wᵉhalᵉwiyyim lᵉmaʿan yiḥzᵃqû bᵉtôrat YHWH</em>) — so that they might be strong in (<em>yiḥzaq</em> = strengthen themselves in) the Torah of the LORD. The economic logic: Levites cannot maintain both agricultural livelihood and full-time temple service without communal support. The Mosaic tithe system (Num 18:21-24) assigned the tithe specifically to Levites as their inheritance in lieu of landed property; Hezekiah re-activates this provision that had apparently lapsed. The goal is explicitly stated: their material security enables their full dedication to Torah-teaching and temple service.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The abundant firstfruits (<em>rēʾšît dāgān tîrôš wᵉyiṣhār ûḏᵉḇaš wᵉḵōl tᵉḇûʾat śādeh</em>) correspond to the Mosaic firstfruit requirements: grain, wine, oil, honey, and all field produce (Deut 18:4; 26:2-10; Num 18:13). The tithe (<em>maʿᵉśēr mikkōl</em>) is the standard 10% of agricultural produce (Lev 27:30-33; Num 18:21; Deut 14:22-29). The word <em>lārōḇ</em> (in abundance) emphasizes that the people exceeded the minimum requirement — a popular overflow rather than reluctant compliance. The season: immediately after the Passover (second month) = late spring/early summer harvest time.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The tithe of cattle and sheep (<em>maʿᵉśar bāqār wāṣōʾn</em>) corresponds to Lev 27:32-33 (the tithe of herd and flock). <em>ûmaʿᵉśar qᵉdāšîm hamᵉquddāšîm lYHWH</em> (tithe of things dedicated to the LORD) — dedicated items beyond the standard tithe, voluntarily consecrated. <em>wayyittᵉnû ḥᵃmārîm ḥᵃmārîm</em> (&lsquo;laying them out in heaps&rsquo;) — the <em>ḥōmer</em> (heap) motif recurs in the abundant donation narrative; the heaps function as visible demonstrations of agricultural surplus offered to YHWH.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The chronological notation — third month to seventh month — reflects the agricultural calendar precisely. The third month (Sivan, May-June) is when the grain harvest was completed and the Feast of Weeks (Shavuot/Pentecost) was celebrated (Num 28:26; Deut 16:9-12): the firstfruits of the grain harvest. The seventh month (Tishri, September-October) is the time of the final ingathering (Feast of Booths/Sukkot, Lev 23:33-44; Num 29:12-38), when the olive and vine harvests were complete. The collection thus runs from the spring grain harvest through the fall fruit harvest, encompassing the entire agricultural year&rsquo;s production cycle.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Hezekiah and the officials inspect the heaps (<em>wayyirʾû ʾet-hāʿᵃrēmôt</em>) and bless both YHWH and his people Israel (<em>wayyᵉḇārᵃḵû ʾet-YHWH wᵉʾēt Yiśrāʾēl ʿammô</em>). The royal inspection of contributed goods and the consequent blessing mirrors the priestly inspection of vows and their pronouncement of acceptability. Hezekiah&rsquo;s blessing of both YHWH (for providing abundance) and Israel (for giving faithfully) makes the king the mediating figure between the community&rsquo;s generosity and YHWH&rsquo;s blessing.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Hezekiah&rsquo;s questioning of the priests and Levites about the heaps — <em>wayyidroš Yᵉḥizqiyyāhû ʿal-hāʿᵃrēmôt</em> — uses the verb <em>dāraš</em> (to inquire/investigate) in an administrative context. The royal inquiry creates the occasion for Azariah the chief priest to deliver the astonishing report of v10. The Chronicler structures this as a dialogue sequence: king asks → priest answers → abundance confirmed, drawing out the theological lesson through the narrative progression rather than stating it didactically.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Azariah the chief priest of the Zadokite line (<em>hakkōhēn hārōʾš lᵉbêt Ṣādôq</em>) — Zadok&rsquo;s line maintained the chief priesthood from Solomon&rsquo;s reign onward (1 Kgs 2:35); Azariah&rsquo;s identification as Zadokite traces the office through a continuous legitimate line. His report: <em>mēhāḥēl hattᵉrûmāh lāḇîʾ bêt-YHWH āḵalnû wᵉnisbaʿnû wᵉhôtēr lārōḇ</em> (since they began bringing offerings to the LORD&rsquo;s house, we have eaten and had enough, with plenty left over) — the three verbs (eaten, satisfied, left-over) express the three levels of agricultural blessing in Lev 26:5: you will eat your fill, you will live securely, you will have surplus.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The command to prepare storage rooms (<em>lišḵôt</em>) in the temple complex — individual chambers within the temple precincts used for storage of dedicated goods, priestly vestments, tithes, and cultic equipment. The temple&rsquo;s storage chambers are mentioned throughout Chronicles (1 Chr 9:26-27; 2 Chr 8:15) as part of the temple&rsquo;s administrative infrastructure. In Second Temple period texts (Neh 10:37-40; 13:12-13), the storage chambers (same term) are the designated depositories for the tithe system, suggesting continuity of institutional practice from Hezekiah through the post-exilic period.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The three categories of dedicated goods: <em>tᵉrûmāh</em> (contribution/heave offering), <em>maʿᵉśēr</em> (tithe), and <em>qᵉdāšîm</em> (dedicated things). <em>Cononiah the Levite</em> (<em>Kônanyāhû halēwî</em>) — his name means &lsquo;the LORD has established&rsquo; — is appointed chief overseer, with his brother Shimei as assistant. The administrative hierarchy for managing the tithes (v13 lists ten additional overseers) reflects the scale of the operation: the tithe administration has become a major organizational challenge requiring professional management.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The ten named overseers under Cononiah and Shimei are appointed by both royal and priestly authority: <em>ʿal-pî Yᵉḥizqiyyāhû hammelek wᵉʿAzaryāhû nᵉgîd bêt-hāʾĕlōhîm</em> (by the appointment of King Hezekiah and Azariah, the chief officer of the house of God). The dual appointment — civil royal authority + religious priestly authority — for the tithe administration models the church-state administrative cooperation that characterizes Chronicles&rsquo; ideal governance. Neither institution monopolizes the management of sacred resources.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Kore son of Imnah, keeper of the East Gate (<em>šōmēr šaʿar hammizrāḥ</em>), is in charge of freewill offerings (<em>nᵉdāḇôt hāʾĕlōhîm</em>) and distribution. The East Gate of the temple was the main ceremonial entrance; its keeper held a position of honor and visibility. <em>laḵōhᵃnîm ûlalᵉwiyyim</em> (to the priests and Levites) — the distribution responsibility covers both the priestly portions reserved by law (Lev 7:28-36; Num 18:8-20) and the Levitical portions (Num 18:21-24), ensuring each class receives what the Torah prescribes.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The six named distribution officers in the priestly cities (<em>ʾEden ûMinḵāmîn ûYēšûaʿ ûŠemaʿyāhû waʾAmaryāhû ûŠeḵanyāhû bᵉʿārê hakᵉhūnîm</em>) manage the distribution network outside Jerusalem. The Levitical cities — 48 towns assigned to Levites and priests throughout Israel (Num 35:1-8; Josh 21) — are the distribution nodes for the tithe system: the agricultural produce tithed in each district needs to be delivered to the Levites and priests living in the nearest priestly city. The phrase <em>ʾɛmûnāh</em> (faithfully) describes their administrative conduct.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Distribution to every male from three years old (<em>mibbên šelōšāh šānîm wāmaʿlāh</em>) who enters the temple for service in their assigned divisions. The age of three for beginning priestly portions is unusual; the Mosaic text prescribes Levitical service starting at 30 (Num 4:3) or 25 (Num 8:24), reduced by David to 20 (1 Chr 23:24, 27). The age three for receiving a food portion (not for service) may reflect a practice of including young children in the family food allotment from the priestly household as soon as they could eat solid food — a practical adaptation for supporting priestly families with young children.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The Levites enrolled from twenty years old (<em>mibben ʿeśrîm šānāh wāmaʿlāh</em>) reflects the Davidic revision of the age threshold for Levitical service (1 Chr 23:24, 27), lowering it from the Mosaic thirty (Num 4:3) or twenty-five (Num 8:24) to twenty. The Chronicler consistently uses the twenty-year threshold as established by David&rsquo;s administrative reform — the earlier ages were appropriate for the physically demanding wilderness tabernacle transport, which was no longer needed once the temple provided a permanent structure.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The genealogical enrollment of the entire priestly household: <em>ûlᵉhityahēś bᵉkol-ṭappām nᵉšêhem ûḇᵉnêhem ûḇᵉnōtêhem lᵉkol-qāhāl</em> (enrolled in genealogy with all their young children, wives, sons, and daughters — the whole community). The genealogical registers (<em>yiḥûś</em>, genealogical record) of priestly families were critical for maintaining cultic legitimacy; only those who could establish their genealogy could function as priests (cf. Ezra 2:61-63, where priests unable to establish their genealogy were excluded from service). The phrase <em>bᵉhiqqaddᵉšām beqōḏeš</em> (in their faithfully consecrating themselves in holiness) ties registration to active maintenance of ritual status.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The provision for priests in the Levitical city pasture-lands (<em>ʾet-bᵉnê ʾahăron hakōhănim bimgrᵉšê ʿārêhem</em>) — those living outside Jerusalem in the common lands of priestly cities received their portions through designated distribution agents. The <em>migrāšîm</em> (pasture-lands/common lands) surrounding the priestly cities were non-arable common property attached to each town (Num 35:4-5), available for livestock grazing but not for agricultural cultivation. Priests and Levites living in these cities needed their portions delivered since they were not in Jerusalem to collect them directly.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The Chronicler&rsquo;s summary verdict on Hezekiah&rsquo;s reform: <em>wayyaʿaś kōh ḥizqiyyāhû bᵉḵol-Yᵉhûdāh wayyaʿaś haṭṭôḇ wᵉhayyāšār wᵉhāʾĕmet lipnê YHWH ʾĕlōhāyw</em> (thus Hezekiah acted throughout all Judah, doing what was good and right and faithful before the LORD his God). The triad <em>ṭôḇ, yāšār, ʾĕmet</em> (good, right, faithful) is the fullest moral summary in Chronicles, applied elsewhere only to David (1 Chr 29:17). The geographic scope <em>bᵉḵol-Yᵉhûdāh</em> (throughout all Judah) ensures that the evaluation covers the whole kingdom, not merely Jerusalem.</p>",
    "21": "<p>&lsquo;In every work he undertook in the service of the house of God, in the law, and in the commandments, seeking his God with all his heart — he prospered&rsquo; (<em>ûḇᵉḵol-maʿᵃśeh ʾăšer-hēḥēl bᵃʿăḇōdat bêt-hāʾĕlōhîm ûḇattôrāh ûḇammiṣwāh liḏrōš ʾĕlōhāyw bᵉḵal-lᵉḇāḇô ʿāśāh wayyaṣlîaḥ</em>). The three-fold scope of Hezekiah&rsquo;s successful service — temple service, Torah observance, and commandment-keeping — represents the comprehensive covenant life. The formula <em>liḏrōš bᵉḵal-lᵉḇāḇô</em> (seeking with all his heart) is the Chronicler&rsquo;s supreme criterion applied to its highest degree; the result, <em>wayyaṣlîaḥ</em> (he prospered), is the immediate covenant consequence. This verse is the structural hinge before ch32&rsquo;s Assyrian crisis, which Hezekiah&rsquo;s wholehearted seeking enables him to survive.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    c = load_comm('mkt-context', '2chronicles')
    merge_comm(c, CONTEXT)
    save_comm('mkt-context', '2chronicles', c)
    count = sum(len(v) for v in CONTEXT.values())
    print(f'2chronicles mkt-context ch29-31: wrote {count} verses')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
